.TH SHOREWALL-NFT-NFSETS 5 "2026-04-20" "shorewall-nft 1.10.0" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
shorewall\-nft\-nfsets \- named dynamic nft sets for shorewall-nft
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.I nfsets
file declares named dynamic nft sets that are populated at runtime by
.BR shorewalld (8).
Each row names a set and selects the backend that will keep it populated.

Declared sets can be referenced in the
.I rules
file using
.IB zone : nfset: name
syntax.  The compiler emits the nft set declarations (type, flags, size);
shorewalld provides the elements.

Use
.I nfsets
instead of inline
.B dns:hostname
syntax when you need:
.IP \(bu 2
Multiple hostnames merged into a single set.
.IP \(bu 2
Non-DNS backends (URL blocklists, cloud provider prefix lists).
.IP \(bu 2
Explicit set naming for tooling and monitoring.

.SH FILE FORMAT
Location:
.I /etc/shorewall/nfsets
(or inside a merged
.IR /etc/shorewall46/ ).
.PP
Columns are whitespace-separated.  Lines beginning with
.B #
are comments.

.TS
l l l.
Column	Required	Description
_
NAME	yes	Logical set name; used in nfset:<name> rule syntax
HOSTS	yes	Hostname(s), URL, file path, or cloud-provider keyword
OPTIONS	yes	Backend keyword + per-backend options (comma-separated)
.TE

Multiple rows with the same
.I NAME
are merged: their
.I HOSTS
lists are concatenated and the backend must be the same in all rows.

.SS Brace expansion
The
.I HOSTS
column supports simple (non-nested) brace expansion:
.PP
.RS
.nf
{a,b,c}.cdn.example.com
  \(->  a.cdn.example.com  b.cdn.example.com  c.cdn.example.com
.fi
.RE

.SH BACKENDS

.SS dnstap
shorewalld intercepts DNS answers from a dnstap or PowerDNS protobuf
stream and installs the resolved A/AAAA records into the nft set with
the answer's TTL as the element timeout.

.I HOSTS
entries must be DNS hostnames (qnames).

.I Options:
.TP
.BI dnstype= a | aaaa
Restrict to one address family only.
.PP
.RS
Example:
.nf
web   {cdn,static}.example.com   dnstap
web   api.example.com            dnstap,dnstype=a
.fi
.RE

Emits:
.RS
.nf
set nfset_web_v4 { type ipv4_addr; flags timeout; size 4096; }
set nfset_web_v6 { type ipv6_addr; flags timeout; size 4096; }
.fi
.RE

.SS resolver
shorewalld actively resolves each hostname on a TTL-driven schedule and
installs the resolved IPs with the answer's TTL as an element timeout.
Use this backend when you cannot deploy dnstap (e.g. an upstream resolver
you do not control).

.I HOSTS
entries must be DNS hostnames.

.I Options:
.TP
.BI dns= IP
DNS server to query.  Can be specified multiple times for multiple servers.
.TP
.BI refresh= DURATION
Minimum re-resolve interval (e.g.
.BR 5m ,
.BR 1h ).
.TP
.BI dnstype= a | aaaa
Restrict to one address family.
.PP
.RS
Example:
.nf
cdn  api.example.com www.example.com  resolver,dns=198.51.100.53,refresh=5m
.fi
.RE

.SS ip-list
shorewalld fetches a structured prefix list from a registered cloud
provider (AWS, GCP, …) and installs the prefixes/CIDRs into an interval nft
set.

.I HOSTS
must be the registered provider keyword (e.g.
.BR aws ,
.BR gcp ).

.I Options:
.TP
.BI filter= dim = val
Provider-specific filter dimension, for example
.BR filter=region=us\-east\-1 .
.TP
.BI refresh= DURATION
Re-fetch interval (default: 1 h).
.PP
.RS
Example:
.nf
aws\-ec2  aws  ip\-list,filter=region=us\-east\-1,refresh=6h
.fi
.RE

Emits:
.RS
.nf
set nfset_aws_ec2_v4 { type ipv4_addr; flags interval; size 262144; }
set nfset_aws_ec2_v6 { type ipv6_addr; flags interval; size 262144; }
.fi
.RE

.SS ip-list-plain
shorewalld reads one IP or CIDR per line from an HTTP(S) URL, an absolute
file path, or a script whose stdout is the list.

.I HOSTS
must be exactly one source: a URL beginning with
.BR http:// " or " https:// ,
an absolute path (beginning with
.BR / ),
or a command prefixed with
.BR exec: .

.I Options:
.TP
.BI refresh= DURATION
Re-fetch interval (default: 1 h).
.TP
.B inotify
For file paths only: trigger an immediate reload when the file changes
(via inotify).
.PP
.RS
Examples:
.nf
# URL-backed blocklist
blocklist   https://example.org/block.txt  ip\-list\-plain

# Local file, reload on change
localblock  /var/lib/lists/blocked.txt     ip\-list\-plain,inotify

# Script-generated list, refresh every 15 minutes
dynblock    exec:/usr/local/bin/gen\-list   ip\-list\-plain,refresh=15m
.fi
.RE

.SH OPTIONS REFERENCE
.TS
l l l.
Option	Backends	Description
_
dnstap	\(em	Backend keyword
resolver	\(em	Backend keyword
ip-list	\(em	Backend keyword
ip-list-plain	\(em	Backend keyword
dns=IP	resolver	DNS server; repeatable
filter=dim=val	ip-list	Provider filter dimension
refresh=DURATION	resolver, ip-list, ip-list-plain	Re-fetch/re-resolve interval
inotify	ip-list-plain	Watch file via inotify
dnstype=a/aaaa	dnstap, resolver	Address family restriction
.TE

Duration syntax: integer seconds, or integer followed by
.BR s ,
.BR m ,
.BR h ,
or
.BR d .
Examples:
.BR 300 ,
.BR 5m ,
.BR 1h ,
.BR 2d .

.SH nft SET NAMING
Each declared set produces two nft sets — one for IPv4 and one for IPv6:
.RS
.nf
nfset_<name>_v4
nfset_<name>_v6
.fi
.RE

Name sanitisation: the logical name is lowercased; non-alphanumeric
characters become
.BR _ ;
consecutive underscores are collapsed; the body is truncated to 22
characters with a SHA-1 collision guard appended if needed.  The maximum
total identifier length is 31 characters.

.SH REFERENCING SETS IN RULES

.TP
.IB zone : nfset: name
Match packets whose source or destination address is in the set.
.TP
.IB zone :! nfset: name
Match packets whose address is
.I not
in the set.
.TP
.IB zone : nfset: name1 , name2
Comma-separated list: expands to one rule per set.

.SS Example rules
.RS
.nf
#ACTION  SOURCE               DEST   PROTO  DPORT
ACCEPT   net:nfset:cdn        loc
ACCEPT   loc                  net:nfset:allowlist
DROP     net:!nfset:trusted   fw
.fi
.RE

.SH nft SET FLAGS
The compiler selects
.B flags
based on the mix of backends:

.TS
l l.
Backend mix	nft flags
_
All dnstap / resolver	flags timeout
All ip-list / ip-list-plain	flags interval
Mixed DNS + ip-list	flags timeout, interval
.TE

Default
.BR size :
512 for DNS-only sets; 65536 when any ip-list backend is present.

.SH RELATIONSHIP TO shorewalld
.PP
The compiler (1) emits the nft set declarations in the compiled ruleset, and
(2) serialises the nfsets registry inside the
.B register-instance
control-socket payload that
.B shorewall\-nft start
sends to shorewalld.

shorewalld's NfSetsManager receives the payload and:
.IP \(bu 2
Routes
.B dnstap
/
.B resolver
entries into the DnsSetTracker pipeline.
.IP \(bu 2
Starts a PlainListTracker for
.B ip-list-plain
sources.
.IP \(bu 2
Passes
.B ip-list
configs to IpListTracker.

Multiple instances in different network namespaces can each declare a set
named
.BR nfset:web
— shorewalld routes DNS answers into the correct nft set in the correct
netns.

.SH INLINE dns: AND dnsr: ALTERNATIVES
Instead of declaring a named set, rules may use inline syntax:
.TP
.IB zone : dns: hostname
Single-hostname tap-driven set (one set per hostname).
.TP
.IB zone : dnsr: hostname
Single-hostname pull-resolver-driven set.
.PP
Use
.B nfset:
when multiple hostnames must share one set or when a non-DNS backend is
needed.

.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/shorewall/nfsets
The nfsets config file.
.TP
.I /etc/shorewall/dnsnames.compiled
Written by
.B shorewall\-nft start
from the set declarations; read by shorewalld as its DNS allowlist.
.TP
.I /var/lib/shorewalld/
shorewalld state directory where DNS set contents are persisted across
daemon restarts.

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR shorewall\-nft (8),
.BR shorewalld (8),
.BR shorewall\-nft\-rules (5),
.BR shorewall\-nft\-zones (5)

